      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Observations\n\n- **K-type constants** dominate the database, accounting for over three-quarters of all entries. These represent stepwise equilibrium constants for successive ligand binding (e.g., K₁, K₂, …), which are the most commonly reported form in experimental coordination chemistry literature.\n- **H-type constants** (≈12%) capture protonation equilibria or mixed-proton metal–ligand systems, reflecting the importance of pH-dependent speciation in real-world solutions.\n- **S-type (β) constants** (≈11%) represent cumulative (overall) stability constants. Although β values are often derived from stepwise K values, many authors report them directly, especially for higher-order complexes where stepwise resolution is difficult.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
